      <string id="gpupdate_drive_maps_home_user">Mapping user's network drives in the home directory</string>
      <string id="gpupdate_drive_maps_home_user_help">Mapping user's network drives in the home directory

Disabled (default) — symbolic links to user's network drives mount points will not be placed in the home directory.

Enabled — symbolic links to user's network drives mount points will be displayed in the home directory:

   /run/media/USERNAME/drives -> ~/net.drives — for user's network drives;

   /run/media/USERNAME/.drives -> ~/.net.drives — for hidden user's network drives.
      </string>
      <string id="gpupdate_drive_maps_home">Mapping machine's network drives in the home directory</string>
      <string id="gpupdate_drive_maps_home_help">Mapping machine's network drives in the home directory

Disabled (default) — symbolic links to machine's network drives mount points will not be placed in the home directory.

Enabled — symbolic links to machine's network drives mount points will be displayed in the home directory:

   /media/gpupdate/drives.system -> ~/net.drives.system — for system network drives;

   /media/gpupdate/.drives.system -> ~/.net.drives.system — for hidden system network drives.
      </string>
      <string id="gpupdate_filescopy_applier">Configuring the File Copy Mechanism</string>
      <string id="gpupdate_filescopy_applier_help">Configuring the File Copy Mechanism

This policy allows you to configure the file copying mechanism. Files with certain suffixes (extensions) are granted the right to execute when copying along the specified paths.

If the policy is enabled, you must specify a list of copy paths and a list of suffixes.

When copying files with the specified suffixes along the assigned paths, the right to execute is added.

If the policy is disabled or not configured, the copy mechanism works by default.

Example: If the suffix ".py" is specified in the suffix list, and the path "/usr/bin" is specified in the path list, then files with the suffix ".py" will become executable when copied to the path "/usr/bin".
      </string>

